    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A ball game for two players (or two pairs of players) occupying the same playing area in a four-walled court, in which the ball is directed with a racket against the front wall, points (in the modern game) being won by the server if the opponent is unable to return the ball successfully within the laws of the game. Rackets is distinguished from the more recent game, squash, in particular by the use of a solid, harder ball. Rackets is now played in covered indoor courts, but rackets is known to have been played in open outdoor courts before the 19th century, though the exact nature of the original game is uncertain.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000114707/Oxford English Dictionary Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>由兩位選手（或兩組雙人選手）在四面都是牆的球場中，佔有相同區域，以球拍向前方的牆擊球之球類遊戲，若對方無法根據遊戲規則，成功將球回擊，現代遊戲中則由發球方得分。壁球與近年來的英式壁球有所不同，尤其是前者使用的球材質較為堅固。壁球雖為室內場地運動，十九世紀前卻以戶外場地為主，由來無從得知。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
